segments.text: The following is an interview with Leon Wilhite, assistant director of planning for the state of Texas.
The interview was conducted by Robert Cornish and Kent McLemore on the 2nd of April, 1984 in Austin in the Sam Houston office building in Leon Wilhite's office.
When did you begin your tenure with the state?
I started back in the fall of 1971 under Preston Smith's administration.
that in those days, we had a division of planning coordination.
And that division was really into policy planning.
Under really some national initiatives under HUD 7701, they began encouraging planning responsibilities at the state level.
And we began seeing a number of states create offices
Back in 1969 was one of the first years that there was a division planning coordination.
And Jim Ray was not the first director of the division.
That was under Conley.
But there was a director for about two or three months before Jim Ray took over.
And Jim was one of the first directors, I think one of the first identified directors,
Shortly after Jim Ray left and Preston Smith came on, Dan Petty was the director in 69 under Preston Smith.
And Dan Petty had worked for Bill Pitstick in North Central Texas Council of Governments and was very instrumental in getting some of the early stages of North Central planning activity started.
But under Dan Petty,
the division planning coordination really took hold.
And under Preston Smith, we began seeing some policy planning and some coordination work done.
And in fact, I think during the 69-71 era, just before I was involved, this office was recognized on a national basis as a planning and coordination office, and that model
as a fairly strong planning core coordination type agency.
We got a national award at the national level, I think, in 1970.
Part of all of that recognition came from the old Goals for Texas program that started back in the latter part of 69, carried it through, and was finally, I guess, completed.
It was phase one and phase two, and those were finally completed in the latter part of 1970.
The Goals for Texas, I think, was a real good initiative, one of the first identified statewide planning activities.
And the first phase of it was to identify at the state level what were the key areas.
It broke down the whole planning spectrum down into about 10 categories.
Then after phase one was drawn together, what state agencies thought the issues and the problems were and the goals were, they went out for phase two.
And it was a thicker, more comprehensive effort.
And I remember, Bob, in I'm not sure what year of our planning program, when I was a student over at Bryan College Station, we participated in one of the committees there in Bryan.
And I remember.
several people coming from the state.
And they were trying to get little committees working.
And I remember sitting on the natural resource committee when the goals were being established.

And I really think the key thing about the goals for Texas was it began really talking in terms of goals and objectives and trying to identify what they were and trying to begin in the beginning of each one of those documents
began specifying five-year, seven-year objectives and so on.
I think it did a great deal for beginning a planning dialogue.
It was very unfortunate that, of course, after any governor creates something like a planning initiative or any kind of policy initiative and then goes out of office,
that initiative tends to die down.
There was a Phase I of Goals for Texas II, and then there was a follow-on, so-called Phase III, which was really the budget document.
It was the first year in state government that we went to a program-type budget, and we tried to tie the goals and objectives identified in the Phase I and II into the budget document itself.
This was the early days of back in 73 was the first year the state created a zero-based budgeting concept and was beginning to move into mandating that state agencies develop objectives.
And prior to really 71,
The budget process itself strictly identified personnel, travel, and normal budgetary kinds of cost centers.
It did not in any way lay out budgets on a program basis.
As I said later on, zero-based budgeting came into being and actually picked up and took it on to we now have more of a program type budget.
Phase III was an effort to try to move us from the normal old categorical budget to a program budget.
The Goals for Texas program, isn't it true that it was modeled more or less after the Goals for Dallas?
That had been quite successful a few years before.
I think so.
I think so.
And I would think it probably, since the Dan Petty came from Dallas and Arlington
came from North Central Texas Council of Governments, that the idea might have spawned from that experience.
Quite frankly, during my early days of the governor's office, I had not heard that much about Goals for Dallas prior to Goals for Texas.
Really, Goals for Dallas had another run at it after Goals for Texas, and it seemed to get even more publicity later.
So I did not realize that
Goals for Dallas came first, but I understand later that it did.
The Goals for Texas program resulted in a national APA award for the chapter, which is the only national award the chapter has ever received.
From AIP at that time?
From AIP, yeah.
It was in my office, if you ever needed it.
aware of exactly what role AIP did play at that time.

I don't know that John Shanahan played a role because John was down here during the time that was going on, but John was not in the Division of Planning and Coordination per se, but he was in the Office of State-Local Relations, which was a division in the Governor's office.
But obviously
Did AIP play a role or iChapter play a role in setting up Golds for Texas?
I think that our chapter probably just simply provide a nurturing role.
But if the truth be known, the award probably should have gone to the governor's office rather than chapter.
Well, we got awards.
I think HUD wound up, because of
Obviously, they helped fund some of the earlier work.
And they were real proud of it, I'm sure.
And we got an award there.
And I'm not sure.
I think the National Association of Regional Councils also gave us an award on that.
So there were several awards.
But I think the goal for Texas was.
That might be a good thing to document precisely so that we can put that in.
Which different groups' awards?
You know, that could possibly be documented.
I'm not sure I can.
There's several.
There's one here.
You might stop it if you want to.
It's part of a golden age.
Yeah.
I think one key thing about Goals for Texas was that while regional councils were still being organized, regional planning commissions were still being organized in Texas,
In fact, the last one was organized out at Midland-Odessa in 1971.
So you can tell Goldford, Texas ended in 70, the end of 70.
But most of the regional councils that were organized at that time, that was a very early agenda item that the governor had asked regional councils to help informalize it.
Bragg's Valley Development Council, when I was a student,
was the instrument to help organize and get the local input and the committees set up and all that.
Many of the councils of government had just been transformed from the old EDDs, Economic Development Divisions or whatever, into councils of governments.
Economic Development Districts were formed back in early years.
I'm not sure when the first one was formed, but

In the latter 60s and then early 70s, we began trying to, as a policy of the governor, in fact, Governor Smith, we began folding regional, really the districts into regional councils and trying to merge them.
There's still two or three that still exist.
Even after we pressed a lot trying to force them into one organization, there's still two or three that currently exist.
Brazos Valley Development Council was one example of a district that became the regional council of Brazos Valley Development Council.
What is the status of the regional planning areas now that are focused around COGS?
The state's been divided into planning regions.
Are those still existing?
Yes.
State planning regions still exist.
The last time that we've had a county change was 1973.
We've been laboring extensively trying to keep those regions somewhat consistent and sacred, although we review the boundaries every two years under law.
We have tried to encourage that they stay the same, and we try to use the regions.
Each 24 of the 24 regions are multiples thereof in planning activities.
So we've seen for planning, and then many agencies are trying to use the regions as best they can for operational purposes, program operations.
Most of the human service type agencies are finding that
They need anywhere from 10 to 12 regions rather than 24, so they make combinations thereof.

But we've continued over 10 or 12 years to push for the geographic framework so that, you know, Texas has 254 counties and is extremely diverse and over 3,000 cities and various and sundry kinds of cities.
And it's almost mandated that we look at some multiples of all of those to be able to handle any kind of activity.
So state-planning regions are still a vehicle we're using.
Conley formed the regions initially in 1968 after a consultant study.
They tried to form regions where you had
A metropolitan area, primarily one of the first things we looked for was an SMSA.
And then we tried to align counties that were naturally drawn to that metropolitan area, both economically, geographically.
And there were about nine specific criteria used to determine where a county would be aligned.
And our studies every two years have tried to reiterate those criteria to determine
where it would go.
We've had counties officially request movement.
We've had to go out and meet with the counties and cities and citizenry.
And to really go through that criteria with them, we find that usually those things, after they're all settled down, everybody feels like they're aligned about right.
So it was all based on a 68 study.
Conley started it.
under Preston Smith, policy development in regard to playing regions became a fairly major issue.
We moved into some fairly heavy-handed positions of mandating that counties move here and there and that state agencies shall use.
During the years from 71 through Briscoe administration, the playing regions were intact, but
not forcefully implemented.
State agencies began drifting away and doing other kinds of things.
But planning regions stayed intact since that time, since really 68.
And the only major change, the last major change, was in 73.
So I think we do have the geographic framework for our planning and state agencies
Right now, I guess, if you drew a bottom line, try to use them, although we've got issues like river authorities.
The water agency, for example, has a hard time using planning regions because river basins do not really recognize political boundaries.
When you're dealing with water issues, basically, Bob's an expert in that.
you really do not do well by trying to go off of political boundaries for that basis.
So we've struggled a little bit with those kinds of issues, how you deal with environmental concerns that really do not recognize boundaries.
But we're dealing with a big one right now with Canada, for example, on acid rain that doesn't recognize an international boundary, for example.

Well, okay, on the state planning reasons, could you give us the benefit of your experience with the Smith administration and the sort of thing that Governor Smith was attempting to establish for the state's role in planning and how that came about and who the principal players were in all of that?
I think, as I mentioned, Gold for Texas was one keynote.

I think the latter part of the Smith administration, in fact, just before losing the election, and then by January after, in the process of leaving, there were a number of documents published that were really
And we look back on those documents as being now some real valuable cornerstones, if you will.
There were a number of planning policies established, policies about economic development districts moving from districts doing their own thing to being a part of the regular planning system.
Those documents were policies that if

If Smith had been around for a while and the players as they were at that time, we would have seen, we would have for sure not seen three economic development districts floating around out there by themselves right now.
There were just a lot of those kinds of things that were being forced at that time.
Ed Grisham was the director of the division planning coordination at that time.
under Preston Smith, and I would think would have to be identified as a key person.
After Dan Petty moved over to the governor's executive assistant position, he handpicked Ed Grisham.
And Ed, Bob, I mentioned Ed as being the new chairman of the Texas Employment Commission over now.
But Ed was a very, in fact, Ed was the point guy for Dan Petty on the Goals for Texas program.
He was the staffer.
that did a lot of the nuts and bolts work.
Where did Ed come from?
Ed was a Texan, and somewhere sort of west, central Texas somewhere, I'm not sure, the little town, but had gone to school out of sort of the landscape program, I think, out at Texas Tech.
and had worked for the Department of Agriculture within Washington for some time.
I'm not sure, a short time.
He was a young guy.
When he was a director here, he was about 32.
And so he was still young and had a lot of vinegar.
And Ed was the director.
Another key actor in that division was Walter Tibbetts, as I mentioned to you, is now back as a part of the governor's staff.
And Walter was the person that hired me and was involved in hiring several people that really carried the office from about 71 through probably around 74 or 75.
There were quite a few of our people that carried quite a bit of initiatives and so on.
Up to my hiring.
There had never been anybody with any kind of planning degree.
Most everybody in this office was a public administrator, a government major, and even Ed Grisham, while having a landscape type background, was not out of a planning program.
And in 71, I was hired by a guy named Tony Briard that came out
the University of Texas Planning School.
We were the two that were hired in 1971, sort of the first so-called graduated, educated planner types.
And it was sort of interesting.
While they were getting these national awards from planning organizations and all that, they were all saying, but we're not planners.
I want you to make sure that you understand that we appreciate
the planning principles, but we're not planners.
And I remember Dan Petty always referring to planner types and planners, but he was always the one that was really pushing setting up goals, programs, and so forth.
Most everybody had the concept of a planner being a street grid system layout person that really did very structural planning activities.
They really didn't view planning as a process where, really, decisions are made.
And I think that's been my song throughout day one, is that planning is just a structured decision-making process.
And that during the middle 70s, I'll just say to you that planning was viewed as land use planning.
When you said planning, you meant regulating land and its use.
And during that period of time, that was a no-no, very much a no-no.
And so even people started dropping the planning name.
They were very fearful of turning folks off from planning.
And I continually, throughout those periods of time, tried to get people to view planning as a process.
And as laying the options out to the governor, we can make a good decision.
And that's what planning is all about, and trying to transcend this cloud of this nasty process and concern.
It seems like you then were part of the cutting edge of the new movement of redefining the planning process and what planning is about.
Because prior to, well, the decade of the 70s, planning was largely focused on land use planning.
There's no question about that.
And it was all pretty physical.
And then with the discovery of the environment and so forth, that was reiterated.
But then we went on to other things and redefining it as a management tool.
And it's interesting that you were here in Austin carrying that word.
at the very time that it was being done all around the country, actually.
And so we weren't in any way lagging behind the rest of the country at that point.
In fact, probably we were right at the cutting edge of it.
I really think, and I contribute a lot to the playing school at A&M.
I came out of the architecture program, so therefore I was very much oriented toward the physical view of things.
Most of my coursework, outside of the structure of the curriculum that I had to take, was very much oriented in sociology.
Some of the business courses I took, quite a few courses, philosophy and things like that, took me really away from sort of that physical thing.
And it really had an impact on me.
some of the people politically were very much more to the left of where I was.
I grew up in East Texas, very much conservative in political perspective.
I went to the core, was in architecture school.
And I remember taking a course in my fifth year architecture school.
And some of the social principles and discussion that were going on in those classes were just,
blowing my socks off.
I mean, it really took me a while to even be able to be in the same room with some of this discussion going on.
And while I look back now, I've gained a lot in the social side of planning and the human side of the issues in that experience.
And I think I've broadened tremendously in trying
see what planning or decision-making really does to society.
And I think it was one key value that I got out of playing school, out of the whole thing.

I think it forced me, even though it was uncomfortable, and I didn't really feel good about a lot of things that went on in graduate school, because I was being forced in all those cases to go beyond where I was.
And it was a forcing, almost a two-year, very
rigorous forcing process.
That's what we hope to do.
Well, and being at A&M, you'd never dream that that would happen.
I think you pressed a lot, Bob, as a person from California and looking at where you had been.
I think McGraw and Gardner and a lot of those folks were people that were really pushing us
Yeah, yeah.
But I think it was valuable.
I'm trying to think of things that we might move into.
One of the first assignments I had down here was trying to coordinate activities going on at the state level.
And the human service business, the coordination of planning activities within each state agency was one of the first assignments I had.

while having an architecture background, having, you know, began some of this acclimation, I might say, of this process, then to have one of the first assignments is to deal with human service agencies was a real challenge to me.
And I began getting into family planning kinds of issues, began viewing health planning, what was going on in health planning,
What did our human service agencies, what kinds of services were being provided, what kind of services at the health department?
It really gave me a bath real early of activities at the state level that I had never been introduced to before.
So I guess trying to carry where we were back in the 69, 70 era,
One of the key things that were done is we passed a law that created the governor as chief planning officer.
It said that the governor shall create interagency planning councils to transcend agencies and concerns.
And I think that was when, if you want to try to pull that up, it's Article 44.13.32a.
And it is a state law that gives a basis for the governor being involved in planning, really.
The law back in 69 and 70 talked more extensively about interagency planning councils, what they should be, and so forth.
In 75, the law was amended to be a little bit more general, giving the governor some authorities in planning
expanded some roles, but really got a little bit more general in the interagency council area.
HUD required each state to designate a state planning officer, as I recall, for the transmittal of monies and so forth to sign off on plans and programs that would receive federal grants.
And most states, in fact, did specify the governor as a state planning officer.
But it didn't necessarily follow them.
I think that that happened about the time that you're mentioning here.
About that same time, in 69, the Intergovernmental Cooperation Act was passed.
It was passed actually in 67, I believe.
The Demonstration of Cities and Metropolitan Act was passed in 64.
And then the National Environmental Policy Act was passed in 69.
All three of those laws, national laws, gave the grounding to trying to create this review function of federal grants.
And that's really important.
You know, that did occur, and in 69, the division planning coordination was designated as the clearinghouse for federal grants.

But I do not know that I can verify that because of those three federal acts and the old Circa 895 being created by the Office of Management and Budget as being a direct mandate for designating the governor as chief planning officer.
In fact, I think the governor was actually designated prior to that time.
But it might have been the mood that actually came.
I think, in fact, that the governor chief planning officer occurred in 67.
But I would need to check the actual date on when the law was passed.
But having the interagency planning councils, Preston Smith began forming.
councils, particularly in the health area.
As one of my first areas, the Interagency Health and Human Service Council at that time was a coordinating group of about 18 to 20 human service agencies.
And the governor would call this meeting of agency heads.
Governor Smith would always spend about 15 or 20 minutes opening the session.
He'd tend to leave.
then the director of the Division of Planning Coordination would be the guy that pretty well ran the meeting.
And we have quite a bit of early work in coordinating the planning efforts occurred through the Interagency Planning Councils.
That was the Health and Human Service Council I mentioned.
There was one that...
Does that still exist, the Interagency Planning Council?
No.
Not that one.
There is a...
When was that abandoned?
Okay.
As governors came in, left and came in, there tended to be, you know, an ending of that council and a recreation of something.
Briscoe, Governor Briscoe began...
sort of, let me see how I can say it, he began becoming fairly inactive personally as a governor in interagency planning councils.
While they continued to function, his guy was a director of division planning coordination, continued to call meetings and to operate.

When the governor didn't come personally, agency commissioners began dropping out, so they began to be slowly but surely, without commissioners there, you lose decision makers, and pretty soon you begin losing effectiveness.
So I think the latter part of the Briscoe administration, I'd say 76, was probably pretty much the end of the interagency councils in that administration.
That's really about three years out of six that they continue to function and operate.
But a director of a division is actually calling the meetings and setting up meetings and so on.
So Governor Clements then picked up on, quote, the authority and created a group
that they were really the Big 12.
And this is a cross-functional group.
This is natural resource, human services.
It was a group that Governor Clements used as the group to initiate and to operate the employee reduction programs, the employee training programs.
I guess it was called Texas State Government Effectiveness Program.
And this council of the, quote, big 12 state agencies were used as a forum for the governor to kind of implement these policies.
Many of those policies directed planning, impacted planning in a very direct way.
But it was not the same kind of functional planning coordination work that went on in the early 70s
under the Preston Smith era, under the early days of the Briscoe administration.
Let me give you an example of what I think you'll make a little bit clearer.
This document I know, Bob, you have seen.
It's a document that was produced by the Interagency Council on Natural Resources and the Environment.
It was a set of guidelines and procedures for reviewing environmental impact statements and for coordinating issues that were interagency in nature.
This document is really a policy statement of the agencies directly involved in natural resources.
This was adopted May of 75, but it
You know, it is a statement.
I think if you go through here and read the policy, it's called the Policy for the Environment.
It's actually a signed document saying this is what we believe and what we would like to do in trying to address environmental concerns.
This was a far reaching document at that time for us.
fact that we still look on it as a basis that we still refer to and deal with because it was a policy statement.
It did talk about procedures.
It has a statement on the planning process.
I'm sure Bob will really enjoy critiquing.
I know you've seen this, Bob.
Haven't you?
Have you seen this document?
I have.
But it did lay out
what was perceived as the planning process at that time in trying to make decisions about whether to construct a state building or a highway or a reservoir.
This is the process that you go through in trying to determine whether it's a good decision or not.
And I guess just to pass on to a group of planners, this was done primarily because
the state agencies felt that if they didn't take matters into their own hands, that the feds were going to do it to them.
And clearly, you know, that was the underlying feeling throughout this document.
I'd like to say it was because we wanted to do what was good for our state.
And I guess in a way, you know, you might say that might be a part of a reason.
But at any time or most of the time when we had trouble getting some of these things
approved would say, well, you know, if we don't do this, then this is going to happen.
And it clearly was a way of trying to get some key things done.
But this was a product of that council.
And it was a clear, I think, example of how a group of state agencies with functional planning responsibilities get together and try to solve an issue that transcends each of the agencies.
Yeah, when would you say that went out of business, or it hasn't?
This council?
Mm-hmm.
OK.
I mean, the structure of it.
The structure of the council became
I'm trying to remember history.
And if we get down to specific, I'm sure the book will need to, specifics and dates.
I need to get with some experts that might give me that.
But this council was actually transformed into a natural resource council.
They actually deleted the name.
And there was a state law that was passed that created a natural resource council.
After the natural resource council was formed,
Under whose administration?
Well, basically, after Governor Briscoe stopped meeting with this council and stopped, it was obvious that there needed to be some other vehicle.
The state law was passed, which created this Natural Resources Council.
And then, really, the major piece came about to create the Texas Energy and Natural Resources Advisory Council, the 10-rank.

agency you need to pull that law because that law really was the was the major piece that transcended this council there were some interim things between this and uh and that agency but that agency was actually created uh very late in briscoe administration i think probably around uh just just trying to recall 78 probably 77 or 78
Did the membership stay the same?
No.
See, when it was created as the Texas Energy and Natural Resource Advisory Council, it did change.
We'd need to compare, but we could clearly do that for you.
I mean, the members are signatory to this.
And then the TNRAC agency.
I think the TNRAC agency began drawing in such entities as the Attorney General's Office,
some other people that were directly concerned about energy that were not a part of this entity.
I think, for example, the TNRAC, the co-chairmanship of TNRAC was the governor and the lieutenant governor.
The lieutenant governor wasn't a part.
See, the legislative side,
was not a part of this effort at all.
And then when we began having this new creature of the TNRAC, we began seeing the legislative side very much a predominant actor in the thing.
So I think as far as planning policy, there are several things that we'd need to look at.
We'd need to track, see, this work of this council
went back to probably early 70s, 70, 71.
There are key people that I could identify that could give you the nuts and bolts of what happened in the beginning of 71, 72, depending on how far you feel like you need to go.
Joe Harris is one that I would quickly refer you to as a key actor.
and under Preston Smith of the Interagency Natural Resource Council, this long title.
John Gosden was a staffer under Joe Harris, and John's still here, and could pass on some additional detail about the Natural Resource Council.
The other kinds of councils that were formed during those years, there was a transportation council.
And at that time, we had a separate mass transportation agency.
We had the Aeronautics Commission.
We had the Highway Department.
We had TTI over at A&M as a participant.
The council over at University of Texas dealing with transportation was a participant.
At that time, because mass transit agency was separate,
It clearly needed to be a council of transportation agencies to deal with issues.
After, I don't know what time in the 70s, but the Mass Transportation Agency was transformed as a part of the Highway Department.
It became a little bit less of a reason to try to coordinate because the agency was pretty much a public transportation type agency.
There are still people over TTI that believe there needs to be a transportation council to help coordinate policy in the transportation business.
Who's on your faculty now?
Virgil.
Virgil's very interested still in some form of a transportation council that might be a forum for transportation policy.
executive director of AIP, who then went to UMTA.
Who am I trying to recall?
Well, he went from San Diego, actually.
But it doesn't matter.
But at that time, UMTA was very strong within DOT.
And they had quite a bit of money during that era.
And I think that that was one of the reasons why people were getting pretty enthusiastic about forming councils.
Now, the money's sort of dried up.
Around 75 was the end of the Transportation Council.
And there's really nothing since then that even looks like that.
One thing I wanted to ask you was,
What was John Shanahan's role with state planning?
John was before me.
John, shortly after, or maybe before I came on, John left.
I see.
John, I don't even know that John was here any time that I was.
A very short time, if he was.
I remember coming up as a student and seeing where John was officed.
on the first floors of this building and meeting him again.
Of course, he was over at school in my early years of planning school.
But to my knowledge, I really don't know where he left it and what role he might have played in some of the goals for programs.
I think that would have been a contribution if he did.
I believe, as John will tell us,
One of the key things, my perspective was, one of the key things that that division did, they began looking at housing programs early on.
That was one of the early things that they were looking at, partially maybe because of HUD funding.
But I think shortly after John left, one of the key things that they did was begin developing a housing program and housing planning function.
Well, the next person I wanted to ask you to comment on is Mary Lou Henry and others who were involved in the state's review council to certify 701 planners.
Okay.
And Texas was way ahead in most states in providing some minimum level of guarantee to the citizens
responsible planning would take place under the 701 program.
OK. Let me plead ignorance a little bit to this.
From day one, my involvement, 701 planning, and that was one of the activities that we were involved in when I first started.
It was a source of funding and developing an overall program design for the office.
and trying to develop a planning framework and a set of goals and objectives for the agency and so on.
A piece of funding came to the governor's office for statewide planning and working with regional councils and developing a regional planning process.
And the other piece went to the Texas Department of Community Affairs after 1971, after this agency was formed.
And one of the first roles they had was to allocate that planning money out to communities across Texas for the local planning function.
So they became the administering agency for that local pot of funds.
We continued through the years to work closely with the Texas Department of Community Affairs.
